#compdef devnet-compose
# =============================================================================
# devnet-compose — Union's interactive devnet generator.  Part of the Union
#                  cross-chain interoperability protocol (a trust-minimized,
#                  zero-knowledge bridging protocol designed for censorship-
#                  resistant cross-chain messaging across Cosmos / Ethereum
#                  / EVM-compatible chains).  devnet-compose drops the
#                  developer into an interactive multiselect TUI to pick
#                  which networks (Union, Osmosis, Stargaze, Simd) and
#                  which IBC connections to include, then generates a
#                  `process-compose.yml` describing the full devnet stack
#                  (each network's daemon, the Galois zk-prover, the
#                  Voyager IBC relayer) ready to be launched via
#                  `nix run .#devnet`.  Zero CLI flags — devnet-compose
#                  is a PURE INTERACTIVE TUI: every choice is presented
#                  as a cliclack multiselect prompt.
#
# Author:  Union Labs (unionlabs developer team — Karel Kubat, Aeolun,
#          et al; Union is the Cosmos-native trust-minimized bridging
#          protocol designed by ex-Informal Systems engineers)
# Source:  https://github.com/unionlabs/union/tree/main/devnet-compose
# CLI:     devnet-compose/src/main.rs (uses fadeevab/cliclack — NO clap)
# Library: fadeevab/cliclack
#          ("Beautiful, minimal, opinionated CLI prompts inspired by
#           the Clack NPM package")
# License: MIT (Union); MIT/Apache-2.0 (cliclack)
# Status:  Active — Union has 74016+ stars; devnet-compose is the
#          canonical developer-onboarding TUI for spinning up a local
#          Union devnet for IBC / cross-chain protocol development.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — RUST CROSSES TO 35 SOLO LEAD
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents the
# 35TH Rust CLI library variant.  Rust climbs from 34 to 35 documented
# libraries (fadeevab/cliclack via Union's devnet-compose).  New leaderboard:
# Rust=35 SOLO LEAD, Go=34, TypeScript-Node=34 (three-way tie at 34 from
# R508 broken — Rust now sole top at the R510 DECADE MILESTONE).  Taxonomy
# now spans 249 cross-language CLI library variants across 60 documented
# languages.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS fadeevab/cliclack AND WHY IS IT A DISTINCT 35TH RUST CLI LIBRARY?
#
# fadeevab/cliclack (https://github.com/fadeevab/cliclack, 343+ stars) is
# **Maksym Fadeev's "Beautiful, minimal, opinionated CLI prompts inspired
# by the Clack NPM package"** — a Rust port and reimagining of
# **@natemoo-re/clack** (the JS interactive-prompt library used by Astro,
# SvelteKit, and other modern JS scaffolders for their `create-X` CLIs).
# Where every previously-documented Rust CLI library focused on argv
# PARSING (clap, structopt, argh, gumdrop, bpaf, lexopt, etc.) or
# application LIFECYCLE (abscissa R502), cliclack focuses on the
# OPPOSITE concern: **INTERACTIVE TUI PROMPTS** — multiselect lists,
# confirm dialogs, text input, password input, progress spinners,
# themed intro/outro banners.
#
# cliclack is DISTINCT from every documented Rust CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. INTERACTIVE-PROMPT-FIRST DESIGN (NOT AN ARGV PARSER) — cliclack
#      is the FIRST Rust CLI library documented in this taxonomy whose
#      primary concern is INTERACTIVE TUI PROMPTS rather than argv
#      parsing.  Compare:
#         clap-derive (R??):    derive-based argv parser
#         structopt (R??):      derive-based argv parser
#         argh (Google):        derive parser, code-size optimized
#         gumdrop:              minimalist derive parser
#         pico-args:            hand-rolled minimal argv parser
#         lexopt:               argument-iterator argv parser
#         bpaf:                 applicative-functor argv parser
#         xflags (matklad):     proc-macro minimal argv parser
#         argparse (tailhook):  Python-argparse-style argv parser
#         seahorse:             fluent-builder argv parser
#         docopt.rs:            USAGE-string-as-spec argv parser
#         paw:                  argument-wrapping trait argv parser
#         getopts:              getopt(3) port argv parser
#         argfile (R498):       pre-parser argv preprocessor
#         argv:                 argument iteration helpers
#         abscissa (R502):      application microframework + argv
#         redox-os/arg-parser:  Redox OS native argv parser
#         palc (R506):          clap-derive drop-in argv parser
#         cliclack (THIS):      INTERACTIVE TUI PROMPTS (no argv parser)
#      cliclack-based binaries either have NO argv (devnet-compose) or
#      pair cliclack with clap for argv (zkstack, goose-cli).  cliclack
#      occupies a fundamentally different layer of the CLI-library
#      stack — **interaction UX**, not parsing.  **First documented
#      Rust CLI library whose primary concern is INTERACTIVE-PROMPT UX
#      rather than argv parsing.**
#
#   2. @natemoo-re/clack JS-LIBRARY PORT — cliclack is an **explicit
#      Rust port of the Clack JS library** (https://github.com/natemoo-re
#      /clack) that powers `npm create astro@latest`, `npm create
#      svelte@latest`, the `create-vue` scaffolder, and other modern JS
#      tool installers.  Clack is **the gold standard** for JS-side
#      "beautiful, minimal CLI prompts" UX — and cliclack brings the
#      same aesthetic to Rust:
#         cliclack::intro(style(" My Tool ").on_cyan().black().bold())
#         let response: bool = cliclack::confirm("Continue?")
#                                      .initial_value(true)
#                                      .interact()?;
#         let networks: Vec<Network> = cliclack::multiselect(
#                                          "Which networks?")
#                                      .item(Union, "Union", "recommended")
#                                      .item(Osmosis, "Osmosis", "")
#                                      .item(Stargaze, "Stargaze", "")
#                                      .interact()?;
#      Compare:
#        @natemoo-re/clack (JS):  same API surface, same theming, same
#                                  styled-banner UX — cliclack-Rust is
#                                  the faithful port.
#        @clack/prompts (JS):     consumed by Astro, SvelteKit, Vue
#                                  scaffolders for `create-*` UX.
#        Inquirer.js (JS):        older, more verbose prompt library
#                                  that Clack was designed to replace.
#      cliclack is **the first Rust CLI library to be a deliberate port
#      of an established JS CLI library**, bringing the JS ecosystem's
#      "modern prompt aesthetic" cross-language.  Cross-pollination
#      with gunshi R504 (Japanese-named TS lib influencing MoonBit's
#      admiral) and Crystal's Admiral (Go-influenced Crystal CLI).
#
#   3. CHAINABLE BUILDER PER PROMPT TYPE — cliclack exposes a SEPARATE
#      BUILDER for each prompt type, each with a fluent chain:
#         cliclack::confirm(msg).initial_value(true).interact()?
#         cliclack::input(msg).default_input("foo")
#                              .validate(|s| if s.len() > 0 {Ok(())} else
#                                            {Err("required")})
#                              .interact()?
#         cliclack::password(msg).mask('*').interact()?
#         cliclack::select(msg).item(value, "label", "hint")
#                              .item(value2, "label2", "")
#                              .interact()?
#         cliclack::multiselect(msg).items(&list)
#                                     .required(false)
#                                     .initial_values(vec![])
#                                     .interact()?
#         cliclack::spinner().start("Working...");
#                  spinner.stop("Done!");
#      Builders implement `.interact() -> Result<T>` returning the
#      typed selection.  Compare:
#        dialoguer (console-rs): similar builder pattern, older library
#        inquire (mikaelmello):  similar builder pattern, more features
#        cliclack:               OPINIONATED MINIMAL surface — fewer
#                                 prompt types, but each with the
#                                 Clack-inspired aesthetic.
#      **First documented Rust CLI library to pursue MINIMAL-PROMPT-
#      TYPE-SET with MAXIMAL-AESTHETIC-COHERENCE.**
#
#   4. THEMING VIA THE `Theme` TRAIT — cliclack lets binaries provide
#      a custom theme by implementing the `Theme` trait, with default
#      methods returning a styled palette:
#         use cliclack::{Theme, ThemeState};
#         struct UnionTheme;
#         impl Theme for UnionTheme {
#             fn state_symbol(&self, state: &ThemeState) -> Style {
#                 // Custom color/symbol per state (Active, Submitted,
#                 // Cancel, Error)
#             }
#             fn format_intro(&self, title: &str) -> Style { ... }
#             // ... 12+ overridable theme methods
#         }
#         cliclack::set_theme(UnionTheme);
#      Compare:
#        dialoguer:    `theme: dyn Theme` trait — similar
#        inquire:      `RenderConfig` struct — comparable
#        cliclack:     `Theme` trait + `set_theme()` global setter —
#                       Clack-faithful theming model, supports per-
#                       binary brand customization (Union uses
#                       UnionTheme; zkstack uses CliclackTheme).
#      Each consumer (Union, zkstack, goose, query) defines its own
#      theme — making cliclack binaries instantly recognizable by their
#      themed intros / banners.
#
#   5. PROGRESS SPINNERS + MULTI-PROGRESS BARS AS FIRST-CLASS PROMPTS —
#      cliclack treats spinners and progress as PROMPT-TYPE-EQUIVALENT:
#         let mut spinner = cliclack::spinner();
#         spinner.start("Downloading...");
#         // ... do work ...
#         spinner.stop("Downloaded!");
#
#         let progress = cliclack::progress_bar(total);
#         progress.start("Processing...");
#         for i in 0..total {
#             progress.inc(1);
#         }
#         progress.stop("Done!");
#      Compare:
#        indicatif (console-rs): canonical Rust progress-bar library,
#                                 SEPARATE from prompts
#        dialoguer:               prompts only, no progress
#        inquire:                 prompts only, no progress
#        cliclack:                UNIFIED — prompts and progress share
#                                  the same theme, the same render
#                                  pipeline, the same intro/outro
#                                  banner sandwich.
#      **First documented Rust CLI library to unify INTERACTIVE PROMPTS
#      with PROGRESS REPORTING under a single theme + render pipeline.**
#
# Bonus: **cliclack is async-AWARE** — most builders accept async work
# wrapped around them, and the spinner's `start()` returns a handle
# that can be passed across tokio tasks for "show spinner while async
# work happens" patterns.  Compare dialoguer (synchronous-only),
# inquire (synchronous-only by default with `async` feature flag).
#
# THE fadeevab/cliclack API SURFACE (verbatim from upstream)
#
#   use cliclack::{intro, outro, confirm, input, password, select,
#                  multiselect, note, spinner, progress_bar,
#                  Theme, ThemeState, set_theme, clear_screen};
#
#   // App framing (intro/outro banner sandwich):
#   intro(style(" My Tool ").on_cyan().black().bold())?;
#   // ... prompts ...
#   outro("All done!")?;
#
#   // Prompt types (each chainable, all return Result<T>):
#   let yes:  bool   = confirm("Continue?").initial_value(true).interact()?;
#   let name: String = input("Your name?").default_input("Anon")
#                                          .validate(non_empty)
#                                          .interact()?;
#   let pwd:  String = password("Password?").mask('*').interact()?;
#   let pick: T      = select("Pick one")
#                          .item(value_a, "Option A", "hint a")
#                          .item(value_b, "Option B", "")
#                          .interact()?;
#   let picks: Vec<T> = multiselect("Pick many")
#                          .items(&[(value_a, "A", "hint"),
#                                  (value_b, "B", "")])
#                          .initial_values(vec![value_a])
#                          .required(false)
#                          .interact()?;
#
#   // Theming:
#   set_theme(MyTheme);  // implements Theme trait
#
#   // Output:
#   note("Title", "info body text")?;
#   log::info(msg)?;
#   log::warning(msg)?;
#   log::error(msg)?;
#   log::success(msg)?;
#   log::step(msg)?;
#   log::remark(msg)?;
#
#   // Progress:
#   let s = spinner();
#   s.start("Working...");
#   s.stop("Done!");
#   let p = progress_bar(100);
#   p.start("Processing...");
#   p.inc(1);
#   p.stop("Done!");
#
#   // Misc:
#   clear_screen()?;
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER RUST CLI LIBRARIES DOCUMENTED IN THE CORPUS
#
#   * clap / clap-derive          — proc-macro derive argv parser
#   * structopt                   — predecessor of clap-derive
#   * argh (Google)               — derive parser, code-size optimized
#   * gumdrop                     — minimalist derive parser
#   * pico-args                   — hand-rolled minimal argv parser
#   * lexopt                      — iterator-based argv parser
#   * bpaf                        — applicative-functor argv parser
#   * xflags (matklad)            — proc-macro minimal argv parser
#   * argparse (tailhook)         — Python-argparse-style argv parser
#   * seahorse                    — fluent-builder argv parser
#   * docopt.rs                   — USAGE-string-as-spec argv parser
#   * paw                         — argument-wrapping trait argv parser
#   * getopts                     — getopt(3) port argv parser
#   * argfile (R498)              — pre-parser argv preprocessor
#   * argv                        — argument iteration helpers
#   * abscissa (R502)             — application microframework + argv
#   * redox-os/arg-parser         — Redox OS native argv parser
#   * palc (R506)                 — clap-derive drop-in argv parser
#   * cliclack (THIS)             — INTERACTIVE-TUI-PROMPT library
#                                    (chainable builders + Theme trait
#                                    + unified prompt+progress under
#                                    Clack-inspired aesthetic)
#
# cliclack occupies a UNIQUE NICHE — the **FIRST Rust CLI library
# documented whose primary concern is INTERACTIVE-PROMPT UX rather
# than argv parsing**.  Every other Rust CLI library variant in the
# taxonomy is an argv-parser of some flavor (derive, builder,
# functional, struct-tag, or hand-rolled).  cliclack is the OTHER
# axis of the CLI-library design space — terminal UX after argv has
# been parsed (or in the absence of argv entirely).
#
# REAL-WORLD fadeevab/cliclack USERS:
#
#   * unionlabs/union:devnet-compose (THIS, 74016*) — pure cliclack
#       devnet generator for the Union zk-bridging protocol
#   * block/goose:goose-cli (46147*) — Block Inc's open-source AI agent
#       framework; uses cliclack for interactive command UX (paired
#       with clap for argv parsing); `goose` binary
#   * matter-labs/zksync-era:zkstack_cli (3243*) — matter labs zkSync
#       Era L2's developer CLI; uses cliclack for interactive prompts
#       paired with clap for argv; `zkstack` binary
#   * gc-victor/query (105*) — Query.run all-in-one web development
#       solution; uses cliclack for user-management interactive prompts
#   * chasebuild/cli-template — official cliclack starter template
#       combining cliclack + clap for new Rust CLI projects
#
# cliclack's adoption pattern: **modern Rust CLIs that want JS-Clack-
# style "beautiful prompts"** — blockchain dev tools (zkstack, Union),
# AI agent framework (goose), web-platform CLIs (Query).  Notable
# adoption from the **Rust blockchain ecosystem** (zkSync, Union)
# where developer onboarding UX is a competitive differentiator.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# DEVNET-COMPOSE'S CLI SURFACE (verbatim from devnet-compose/src/main.rs)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   devnet-compose
#
# devnet-compose takes NO command-line arguments — it is a PURE
# INTERACTIVE TUI.  When launched, it walks the user through:
#
#   1. Banner intro:  "Union Devnet Compose" (UnionTheme styled)
#   2. multiselect:   "Which networks do you want to include?"
#                      - Union (recommended)
#                      - Osmosis
#                      - Stargaze
#                      - Simd
#   3. multiselect:   "Which IBC connections do you want to set up?"
#                      (skipped if only one network selected)
#                      - <netA> <-> <netB> [+ Galois services if Union]
#                      - ... all combinations of selected networks ...
#   4. note:          "Devnet generated!" + tips for log viewing,
#                      process restart, override files
#   5. Output:        writes process-compose.yml to repo root
#
# Run as part of the Union devnet workflow:
#   $ nix run .#devnet-compose
#   $ nix run .#devnet            # launches the generated devnet
#   $ nix run .#devnet-logs       # follows logs of all processes
#
# Themed by `theme::UnionTheme` which customizes:
#   - intro/outro banner background to Union's signature cyan
#   - state symbols (active/submitted/cancel/error) with Union iconography
#   - prompt indentation + spacing for cohesive multi-prompt flow
#
# Since devnet-compose has NO flags, this completion file primarily
# exists to: (1) prevent shell errors when typing `devnet-compose`
# (2) document the taxonomy entry above as the canonical Rust
# cliclack reference, and (3) suggest completion for any nix-run
# wrapper conventions.
#
# =============================================================================

_devnet-compose() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    # devnet-compose takes no CLI args - it's a pure interactive TUI.
    # Provide default file completion in case a user passes a path
    # (which devnet-compose itself would ignore).
    _arguments -C \
        '*: :_files' && ret=0

    return ret
}

_devnet-compose "$@"
